plements the ResourceEventHandler interface. Its OnAdd(), OnUpdate(), and OnDelete() methods receive notifications from processDeltas(). These methods update the local index cache and immediately delegate to the sharedProcessor.distribute() method.\n\n8. **SharedProcessor (shared_informer.go)**: The sharedProcessor maintains a map of all registered processorListeners. Its distribute() method iterates through all listeners and calls listener.add() to queue the notification, considering whether it's a sync event or normal event.\n\n9. **ProcessorListener (shared_informer.go)**: Each registered ResourceEventHandler gets its own processorListener. The listener has two goroutines: pop() which transfers notifications from an unbounded ring buffer to a channel, and run() which reads from that channel and invokes the actual handler methods.\n\n10. **Handler Invocation (shared_informer.go)**: The processorListener.run() method reads notifications from nextCh and invokes the appropriate handler method based on notification type. For addNotification, it calls handler.OnAdd(). For updateNotification, handler.OnUpdate(). For deleteNotification, handler.OnDelete().\n\nThis architecture achieves several goals: (1) Multiple event handlers can register with a single informer via AddEventHandler(); (2) Events are buffered through the DeltaFIFO to handle back-pressure and accumulate changes; (3) Each handler runs in its own goroutine with its own buffer, preventing slow handlers from blocking others; (4) Events are guaranteed to be processed in order for each object; (5) Resync events can trigger re-listing all objects periodically.\n\nThe complete files involved are:\n- ListWatch implementation: tools/cache/listwatch.go\n- Watch event processing: tools/cache/reflector.go (handleAnyWatch, watch methods)\n- Delta accumulation: tools/cache/delta_fifo.go (DeltaFIFO type)\n- Event processing loop: tools/cache/controller.go (processDeltas function)\n- Event distribution to handlers: tools/